<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,151,1184]" pageId="13" pageNumber="168">
<taxonomicName box="[199,410,332,356]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Schizoporellidae" genus="Stylopoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="13" pageNumber="168" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="carioca">
<emphasis box="[199,410,332,356]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="168">Stylopoma carioca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a frontal shield with a porous, rough texture, ribbed calcification and an umbo at the centre of the zooid, an orifice almost as long as wide with a small tab-like condyle, small funnel-shaped median sinus, frontal avicularia which lie flat against the frontal shield surface, and an ooecium with ribs between the marginal pores. 
<taxonomicName box="[337,572,440,464]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Schizoporellidae" genus="Stylopoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="13" pageNumber="168" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="rotundum">
<emphasis box="[337,572,440,464]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="168">Stylopoma rotundum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from the Abrolhos specimens in the rounded frontal avicularia and orifice with thick condyles ending in blunt, downwardly curved hooks. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Pallas" baseAuthorityYear="1766" box="[980,1214,476,500]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Schizoporellidae" genus="Stylopoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="13" pageNumber="168" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="spongites">
<emphasis box="[980,1214,476,500]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="168">Stylopoma spongites</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has smaller zooids (510 µm long x 360 µm wide), an orifice almost as long as wide (100 µm long x 120 µm wide), an anter with sparsely denticulate inner rim, and tall condyles covering a small portion of the proximal margin. There are two kinds of vicarious avicularia: one with a spatulate mandible and the other with a pointed mandible. The labellum is fused to the ooecium leaving a crescent lumen. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Canu &amp; Bassler" authorityYear="1928" box="[715,987,620,644]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Schizoporellidae" genus="Stylopoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="13" pageNumber="168" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="aurantiacum">
<emphasis box="[715,987,620,644]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="168">Stylopoma aurantiacum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the most similar species, but it has smaller autozooids (501 µm long x 423 µm wide) with slightly ribbed calcification and a raised umbo at the centre of the zooid, an orifice as long as wide (120 µm long x 128 µm wide) with a funnel-shaped sinus and commashaped condyles, and lacks interzooidal avicularia; the ovicell is large (581 µm long x 648 µm wide), covering parts of several zooids, with ribs between the marginal pores on the ooecial surface.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="168" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,151,1184]" pageId="13" pageNumber="168">
<taxonomicName authority="Winston &amp; Woollacott, 2009" authorityName="Winston &amp; Woollacott" authorityYear="2009" box="[199,762,799,824]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Schizoporellidae" genus="Stylopoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="13" pageNumber="168" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="haywardi">
<emphasis box="[199,428,800,824]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="168">Stylopoma haywardi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[436,762,799,824]" pageId="13" pageNumber="168" refId="ref21523" refString="Winston, J. E. &amp; Woollacott, R. M. (2009) Scientific results of the Hassler Expedition. Bryozoa. N o. 1. Barbados. Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology, 159 (5), 239 - 300. https: // doi. org / 10.3099 / 0027 - 4100 - 159.5.239" type="journal article">Winston &amp; Woollacott, 2009</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, described from Barbados, has a triangular oral avicularium but with a rostrum ending in a hooked tip, and broad straight condyles occupying almost the entire inner edges of the sinus. 
<taxonomicName authority="Winston, 2005" authorityName="Winston" authorityYear="2005" box="[264,624,871,896]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Schizoporellidae" genus="Stylopoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="13" pageNumber="168" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="smitti">
<emphasis box="[264,450,872,896]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="168">Stylopoma smitti</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[457,624,871,896]" pageId="13" pageNumber="168" refId="ref21261" refString="Winston, J. E. (2005) Re-description and revision of Smitt's &quot; Floridan Bryozoa &quot; in the collection of the Museum of Comparative Zoology, Harvard University. Virginia Museum of Natural History Memoir, 7, 1 - 147. [with an annotated catalogue of specimens collected by L. F. de Pourtales in Florida and Carolina, housed at the Museum of Comparative Zoology, Harvard University]" type="journal article">Winston, 2005</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, described from Florida, shares with 
<taxonomicName authority="Ramalho &amp; Taylor &amp; Moraes &amp; Moura &amp; Amado-Filho &amp; Bastos, 2018" authorityName="Ramalho &amp; Taylor &amp; Moraes &amp; Moura &amp; Amado-Filho &amp; Bastos" authorityYear="2018" box="[1040,1176,872,896]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Schizoporellidae" genus="Stylopoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="13" pageNumber="168" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="variabilis" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[1040,1054,872,895]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="168">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1068,1176,872,896]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="168">variabilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1182,1245,871,896]" pageId="13" pageNumber="168" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1182,1245,871,896]" pageId="13" pageNumber="168">n. sp.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
a similar-shaped orifice and triangular avicularia but can be distinguished by the deeply slit, round-bottomed, almost tear-drop shaped sinus, broad condyles extending almost to the sinus and occasional thickened denticles or tabs on the inner edges of the spatulate avicularia, as well as triangular avicularia on the frontal shield or below the orifice.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,151,1184]" pageId="13" pageNumber="168">
According to bryozoa.net (accessed 
<date box="[616,744,1016,1040]" pageId="13" pageNumber="168" value="2018-01-03">01.03.2018</date>
) there are almost 40 species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ramalho &amp; Taylor &amp; Moraes &amp; Moura &amp; Amado-Filho &amp; Bastos" authorityYear="2018" box="[1115,1232,1016,1040]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Schizoporellidae" genus="Stylopoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="13" pageNumber="168" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1115,1232,1016,1040]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="168">Stylopoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Most are extinct and from the Caribbean and Indo-Pacific. The characteristics of 
<taxonomicName authority="Ramalho &amp; Taylor &amp; Moraes &amp; Moura &amp; Amado-Filho &amp; Bastos, 2018" authorityName="Ramalho &amp; Taylor &amp; Moraes &amp; Moura &amp; Amado-Filho &amp; Bastos" authorityYear="2018" box="[877,1014,1052,1076]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Schizoporellidae" genus="Stylopoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="13" pageNumber="168" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="variabilis" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[877,1014,1052,1076]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="168">S. variabilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1021,1085,1052,1077]" pageId="13" pageNumber="168" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1021,1085,1052,1077]" pageId="13" pageNumber="168">n. sp.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, orifice wider than long with a U- to funnel-shaped sinus, tab-like condyles ending in a downwardly curved tip, single triangular, lateral oral avicularium, vicarious avicularia variable in size with spatulate tip and ovicell globose with ooecial surface perforate and lacking avicularia, distinguish it from other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ramalho &amp; Taylor &amp; Moraes &amp; Moura &amp; Amado-Filho &amp; Bastos" authorityYear="2018" box="[798,915,1160,1184]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Schizoporellidae" genus="Stylopoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="13" pageNumber="168" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[798,915,1160,1184]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="168">Stylopoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species.
</paragraph>
